And an example of that is that I was reading a document one day, a creative direction document,

516
00:24:42,834 --> 00:24:48,696
and it was saying how in this particular poor district there's 70% augmented people who

517
00:24:48,736 --> 00:24:53,418
live there and 30% non-augmented people, so 100% human, we call them I guess.

518
00:24:54,713 --> 00:24:57,054
And I thought it was interesting to give a twist

519
00:24:57,194 --> 00:24:59,115
to an expression set up in the area that I created

520
00:24:59,175 --> 00:25:00,876
about this group called Ad Astra,

521
00:25:01,036 --> 00:25:03,056
who was actually trying to help bridge the gap

522
00:25:03,096 --> 00:25:04,837
between augmented and non-augmented.

523
00:25:04,877 --> 00:25:07,418
It was a cute little story that was pretty optimistic,

524
00:25:07,738 --> 00:25:09,699
and Deus Ex is not optimistic.

525
00:25:10,759 --> 00:25:13,480
So I was actually trying to do something different,

526
00:25:14,540 --> 00:25:19,422
and rewarding with narrative and XP point like this.

527
00:25:20,633 --> 00:25:23,275
Now, I'm done with the narrative part of this talk.

528
00:25:23,415 --> 00:25:24,575
It was pretty important to talk about it,

529
00:25:25,176 --> 00:25:26,617
in my opinion, to help you understand

530
00:25:26,657 --> 00:25:29,658
how we try to design our world and flesh it out.

531
00:25:30,398 --> 00:25:32,099
But exploration is not just about telling stories

532
00:25:32,159 --> 00:25:34,180
and environment storytelling.

533
00:25:34,240 --> 00:25:36,261
It's also about rewarding every other part of the game.

534
00:25:36,922 --> 00:25:41,244
And in our case, we have to benefit using exploration

535
00:25:41,304 --> 00:25:43,125
and navigation, every aspect of the game,

536
00:25:43,645 --> 00:25:45,186
and make all type of content shine.

537
00:25:46,477 --> 00:25:48,018
from the most important, like main missions,

538
00:25:48,238 --> 00:25:49,919
and side missions, to the best kept secrets,

539
00:25:50,139 --> 00:25:52,440
things that people will usually never find.

540
00:25:54,162 --> 00:25:57,944
So, most exploration setups are standalone and original.

541
00:25:58,004 --> 00:25:59,925
Some of them feature special reward

542
00:26:01,546 --> 00:26:03,868
that provide unique advantages during mission.

543
00:26:04,128 --> 00:26:05,169
It's too bad I don't have the sound,

544
00:26:05,189 --> 00:26:09,712
but you can photo that video that gives a vibrant example

545
00:26:09,792 --> 00:26:12,974
of how exploration complements an existing mission.

546
00:26:15,201 --> 00:26:17,163
That's my greatest puzzle you just saw there.

547
00:26:18,244 --> 00:26:20,106
Turn off the TV to find this story item

548
00:26:20,426 --> 00:26:22,448
that is connected to the Palisade Bank.

549
00:26:23,169 --> 00:26:24,090
And if you make the connection,

550
00:26:24,150 --> 00:26:25,832
you go to this area, the bank,

551
00:26:26,753 --> 00:26:30,116
and you meet this guy and you can tell him this.

552
00:26:32,318 --> 00:26:36,523
Use your item to make him like you.

553
00:26:45,177 --> 00:26:49,799
he's not happy that you're an augmented guy and he was taking real pleasure in telling you to

554
00:26:51,259 --> 00:26:57,321
screw yourself. But because you've explored, congratulations, you find this item and you

555
00:26:57,801 --> 00:27:03,543
bypassed, now a whole area of the bank is open to you, your client, you stole his identity,

556
00:27:04,203 --> 00:27:10,785
shame on you, but it allows you to bypass something that would have been very hard

557
00:27:10,805 --> 00:27:14,547
otherwise because the bank is a very difficult mission, full of people like this guy.

558
00:27:16,248 --> 00:27:19,669
So that's one of the way we found to reward main missions

559
00:27:20,129 --> 00:27:20,870
using exploration.

560
00:27:22,130 --> 00:27:24,710
And it's not just about finding story item,

561
00:27:24,750 --> 00:27:27,271
it's also a lot about pure navigation,

562
00:27:27,291 --> 00:27:28,291
so pure level design,

563
00:27:29,112 --> 00:27:32,532
and connecting exploration, narrative,

564
00:27:33,152 --> 00:27:37,013
and how it can connect via sometimes.

565
00:27:39,045 --> 00:27:42,228
alternate path like we like to use in Deus Ex.

566
00:27:42,768 --> 00:27:45,370
So this area is interesting because it's an apartment

567
00:27:45,410 --> 00:27:48,011
of some artist, you don't know what happened there.

568
00:27:48,692 --> 00:27:49,713
There's blood, it's a mess.

569
00:27:50,493 --> 00:27:53,555
So it's a nice little story on its own and I added,

570
00:27:54,296 --> 00:27:56,937
yes, it's an errant, I know people troll about errants,

571
00:27:57,078 --> 00:28:02,001
I'm sorry, I really tried to keep them very small in print.

572
00:28:03,388 --> 00:28:07,690
And this area offers another route towards main mission,

573
00:28:08,210 --> 00:28:09,190
which is a color shop.

574
00:28:10,270 --> 00:28:13,511
And yes, I put a little storytelling piece in that event.

575
00:28:13,651 --> 00:28:15,652
I think it's important to keep events interesting.

576
00:28:16,752 --> 00:28:19,773
And it offers you a new path.

577
00:28:19,813 --> 00:28:23,373
So it's also about connecting various areas

578
00:28:23,473 --> 00:28:25,634
using exploration setups.

579
00:28:27,214 --> 00:28:31,075
And as you may know, when you design a platforming element

580
00:28:31,175 --> 00:28:34,556
for a first person game like ours, it's very weird.

581
00:28:35,476 --> 00:28:40,338
So we try to avoid having a 300 pounds guy

582
00:28:40,438 --> 00:28:41,358
standing on flower pots.

583
00:28:42,898 --> 00:28:45,699
And we do that in different ways.

584
00:28:47,302 --> 00:28:49,223
So that's actually pure visual language,

585
00:28:49,243 --> 00:28:51,144
we need to be very careful about how we entice

586
00:28:51,264 --> 00:28:54,506
our expression routes, how we make people want to

587
00:28:54,646 --> 00:28:56,727
explore something and how not to deceive them.

588
00:28:57,768 --> 00:28:59,029
So we need to have clear, enticing,

589
00:28:59,069 --> 00:29:00,450
integrated navigation platform,

590
00:29:01,070 --> 00:29:02,931
that's a lot harder to do than it looks.

591
00:29:03,892 --> 00:29:05,413
And identifiable navigation threads

592
00:29:05,473 --> 00:29:07,214
from all levels of navigation.

593
00:29:07,294 --> 00:29:08,435
These are just quick example,

594
00:29:08,475 --> 00:29:09,956
I could talk about navigation for hours,

595
00:29:10,016 --> 00:29:11,236
but I don't have time right now.

596
00:29:12,137 --> 00:29:13,458
We have to be able, basically the rule,

597
00:29:13,498 --> 00:29:15,439
where we have to be able to identify a route.

598
00:29:16,793 --> 00:29:19,374
for an exploration setup from anywhere from the ground,

599
00:29:19,414 --> 00:29:22,195
we would see all of these platforms connecting together

600
00:29:22,235 --> 00:29:24,256
and we would know that something is accessible

601
00:29:24,276 --> 00:29:25,417
because in a Deus Ex game,

602
00:29:26,537 --> 00:29:29,878
you never want to lead the player somewhere they cannot go

603
00:29:29,918 --> 00:29:31,919
because we let the player explore everything.

604
00:29:32,420 --> 00:29:34,260
We want the player to be able to access everything

605
00:29:34,580 --> 00:29:35,161
that he sees.

606
00:29:35,701 --> 00:29:36,761
That's the Deus Ex experience.

607
00:29:37,582 --> 00:29:39,743
So we need to remove the navigation clutter

608
00:29:40,243 --> 00:29:42,204
because they betrayed the player's expectation.

609
00:29:42,244 --> 00:29:44,265
That's called affordance, actually.

610
00:29:45,806 --> 00:29:48,787
And it's something that we were very careful about.

611
00:29:48,807 --> 00:29:52,369
If it meant deleting balconies that led to fake windows,

612
00:29:52,789 --> 00:29:53,849
we would do it a lot.

613
00:29:53,949 --> 00:29:57,311
I think I deleted 100 balconies without the artist knowing.

614
00:29:58,611 --> 00:29:59,171
But it's a good thing.

615
00:30:02,032 --> 00:30:02,313
Do it.

616
00:30:04,573 --> 00:30:06,654
And another thing about navigation is that sometimes

617
00:30:06,714 --> 00:30:11,476
it was, we were reaching a point where we didn't really

618
00:30:11,516 --> 00:30:12,597
know how to make it better.

619
00:30:12,617 --> 00:30:13,837
It was too clunky.

620
00:30:15,436 --> 00:30:19,441
At many places it was too weird, you would grab a ledge and you would fall to your death

621
00:30:19,481 --> 00:30:20,803
and it wasn't that funny.

622
00:30:20,843 --> 00:30:26,631
So we used this, the curfew, is, actually it was really a nightmare when it happened

623
00:30:26,651 --> 00:30:28,273
because Prague was never designed.

624
00:30:28,533 --> 00:30:30,196
This is something that happened very late in development.

625
00:30:30,236 --> 00:30:30,636
We had to...

626
00:30:31,477 --> 00:30:34,298
make the city an actual mission,

627
00:30:34,499 --> 00:30:35,739
because there would be cops everywhere.

628
00:30:36,459 --> 00:30:38,700
You walked when you come back from a certain mission.

629
00:30:39,261 --> 00:30:41,121
You cannot navigate the streets however you want,

630
00:30:41,642 --> 00:30:44,203
because people shoot you, police shoot you on site.

631
00:30:45,003 --> 00:30:47,244
And that wasn't something we planned.

632
00:30:47,644 --> 00:30:49,965
We always planned to be able to create chaos in Prague

633
00:30:51,066 --> 00:30:52,126
and let you deal with it.

634
00:30:53,567 --> 00:30:57,268
But we never planned to have a whole map

635
00:30:57,308 --> 00:30:59,969
that would support stealth and combat inside of Prague.

636
00:31:01,130 --> 00:31:04,911
In the end we ended up using it to make everything else better

637
00:31:04,971 --> 00:31:07,691
because navigation had to be really tight for this part of the game.

638
00:31:07,711 --> 00:31:09,452
It had to be possible to escape the cops.

639
00:31:10,632 --> 00:31:13,473
And with this example, it's an area that sucked.

640
00:31:14,713 --> 00:31:16,633
Before we had this constraint.

641
00:31:17,413 --> 00:31:22,695
It was very hard to navigate and because we really worked hard to make...

642
00:31:24,128 --> 00:31:26,589
this possible for the player because we had to,

643
00:31:27,509 --> 00:31:29,170
well it's still pretty hard, this section,

644
00:31:29,570 --> 00:31:30,550
but we had to make it possible.

645
00:31:31,550 --> 00:31:34,451
And it involves tweaking navigation a lot,

646
00:31:34,771 --> 00:31:36,751
so it would be able to do these kind of things.

647
00:31:39,072 --> 00:31:42,473
And bypass cops, or just kill them.

648
00:31:45,033 --> 00:31:46,173
And sometimes we would use,

649
00:31:47,054 --> 00:31:48,514
maybe I shouldn't say that, but we cheated.

650
00:31:49,815 --> 00:31:52,259
If you have the occasion to do it without it showing,

651
00:31:52,319 --> 00:31:54,563
we added collision boxes in some ledges

652
00:31:54,703 --> 00:31:56,827
so you wouldn't fall all the time

653
00:31:57,147 --> 00:31:59,131
and it wouldn't show because you don't see your feet

654
00:31:59,231 --> 00:31:59,591
and it's cool.

655
00:32:01,594 --> 00:32:02,815
But yeah, we cheated a little bit,

656
00:32:02,895 --> 00:32:04,637
but it made the experience a lot better in the end.

657
00:32:05,077 --> 00:32:07,879
And that's an example of how a really tough constraint

658
00:32:08,540 --> 00:32:10,461
helped us make navigation better for the whole city hub

659
00:32:10,501 --> 00:32:12,723
because what we did for the curfew

660
00:32:14,184 --> 00:32:16,086
impacted all of the other visits of Prague

661
00:32:16,126 --> 00:32:17,787
where you don't have to staff around police.

662
00:32:18,148 --> 00:32:19,969
And it's a good idea to think about it.

663
00:32:22,843 --> 00:32:25,904
Now, as in any Deus Ex game,

664
00:32:26,144 --> 00:32:28,545
we give a lot of freedom to player again.

665
00:32:28,705 --> 00:32:31,706
We always have to offer multiple ways to enter a location.

666
00:32:32,926 --> 00:32:35,427
So our navigation always supports every pillar that we have,

667
00:32:35,447 --> 00:32:37,268
so stealth, combat, exploration,

668
00:32:38,528 --> 00:32:40,249
killer profiles, every kind of play types

669
00:32:40,289 --> 00:32:40,989
we have to think about.

670
00:32:43,500 --> 00:32:46,445
And so we put a lot of efforts into avoiding magic locks.

671
00:32:46,966 --> 00:32:48,728
And that's something that always annoys me in games

672
00:32:49,470 --> 00:32:51,032
when they do this kind of thing.

673
00:32:51,713 --> 00:32:52,735
I don't like this kind of thing.

674
00:32:52,855 --> 00:32:55,339
It's putting propping in front of doors.

675
00:32:56,300 --> 00:32:57,242
It's something that we don't.

676
00:32:58,988 --> 00:33:00,509
It's forbidden in Deus Ex to do that.

677
00:33:01,230 --> 00:33:03,952
But sometimes the ID just comes in.

678
00:33:03,992 --> 00:33:05,774
This was an ID that was brought up by someone

679
00:33:05,794 --> 00:33:10,098
a long time ago to prevent an access to one of the banks,

680
00:33:10,759 --> 00:33:12,741
the Palisade Bank, which is a map in Prague, again.

681
00:33:13,441 --> 00:33:14,723
Prevent the access using this.

682
00:33:15,724 --> 00:33:16,144
That sucks.

683
00:33:18,187 --> 00:33:20,590
If you want to block navigation and exploration,

684
00:33:20,630 --> 00:33:24,013
if you want an area to remain locked out

685
00:33:24,073 --> 00:33:26,475
for narrative reason, for critical path reasons,

686
00:33:27,195 --> 00:33:28,937
we tend to do it very clearly.

687
00:33:29,137 --> 00:33:32,620
This is a grid, so it doesn't look very...

688
00:33:33,841 --> 00:33:35,362
I mean, it's still a blockage.

689
00:33:35,822 --> 00:33:39,644
But it's OK, because this area is the Red Lake District.

690
00:33:40,465 --> 00:33:43,366
This is where people go to see naked women

691
00:33:45,387 --> 00:33:48,549
and do other things with augmented women and men.

692
00:33:49,990 --> 00:33:52,833
And it's so enticed when you play,

693
00:33:53,253 --> 00:33:55,355
when you go to Prague and you walk around the street,

694
00:33:55,395 --> 00:33:58,177
everybody explains to you that the red light district is,

695
00:33:58,878 --> 00:34:00,840
it only opens at night, so during the day,

696
00:34:00,880 --> 00:34:02,641
don't expect to be able to go through.

697
00:34:02,681 --> 00:34:05,384
So it's so well integrated into the game

698
00:34:05,404 --> 00:34:07,786
that we know why it's closed.

699
00:34:08,346 --> 00:34:10,348
And if you have to close an area,

700
00:34:11,189 --> 00:34:12,450
if navigation must be controlled,

701
00:34:13,311 --> 00:34:14,392
it must be crystal clear why,

702
00:34:14,412 --> 00:34:15,793
and it's tremendously important.

703
00:34:17,340 --> 00:34:21,162
for us and maybe for you at some point.

704
00:34:22,323 --> 00:34:25,486
And a good example of that, that was the same path

705
00:34:26,546 --> 00:34:29,528
that when I showed you the broomstick in front of the door,

706
00:34:30,409 --> 00:34:32,611
this is what it was meant to block.

707
00:34:32,991 --> 00:34:36,654
This is the secret path to the Palisade Bank

708
00:34:36,694 --> 00:34:38,755
and again, sorry for the spoilers,

709
00:34:38,815 --> 00:34:39,936
it's supposed to be a hard one.

710
00:34:41,277 --> 00:34:44,239
But this area was supposed to be blocked off.

711
00:34:46,632 --> 00:34:48,514
because someone wanted to block it off for,

712
00:34:48,534 --> 00:34:53,499
for no reason, but I had to fight quite hard

713
00:34:53,559 --> 00:34:55,320
to not have it locked.

714
00:34:55,501 --> 00:34:59,044
And we do that because, as you can see,

715
00:34:59,184 --> 00:35:01,427
when we reach this area, this is the,

716
00:35:01,607 --> 00:35:03,849
this is the bank's vault shaft.

717
00:35:04,590 --> 00:35:06,431
This is where you can go anytime you want

718
00:35:06,491 --> 00:35:08,492
because you're gonna find key cards in Prague

719
00:35:08,552 --> 00:35:09,112
if you explore.

720
00:35:10,033 --> 00:35:11,173
They were very well hidden,

721
00:35:11,193 --> 00:35:12,774
so if you found some, congratulations.

722
00:35:13,554 --> 00:35:16,156
And you can go there at all time

723
00:35:16,616 --> 00:35:18,277
to loot these vaults and interesting part of it

724
00:35:18,317 --> 00:35:22,299
is that this is supposed to be an exit to the bank map.

725
00:35:22,539 --> 00:35:23,580
It's not supposed to be an entrance,

726
00:35:24,400 --> 00:35:27,142
but if you really, really are a good explorer.

727
00:35:28,342 --> 00:35:32,085
you can actually enter this area and it's very rewarding in its own way and it's something that

728
00:35:32,965 --> 00:35:36,948
it was worth the fight because it makes the city really more interesting.

729
00:35:40,560 --> 00:35:42,641
And side missions, quickly about them,

730
00:35:43,321 --> 00:35:46,683
they have very different constraints than the main path.

731
00:35:47,083 --> 00:35:50,425
And when I came onto the team,

732
00:35:50,445 --> 00:35:52,466
I was wondering how I could help them

733
00:35:53,626 --> 00:35:56,588
benefit from what we developed in Prague.

734
00:35:57,348 --> 00:35:58,709
And the interesting thing is that side mission

735
00:35:58,749 --> 00:36:01,870
in Human Revolution, they had to put their things

736
00:36:02,030 --> 00:36:04,572
into an existing layout, nothing was made

737
00:36:05,232 --> 00:36:07,253
specifically for the side missions in Human Revolution.

738
00:36:08,093 --> 00:36:09,054
So it was pretty hard for them.

739
00:36:09,114 --> 00:36:10,835
And from the very start of Prague,

740
00:36:11,975 --> 00:36:13,656
we, the level designers, the two of us,

741
00:36:13,796 --> 00:36:15,216
we talked to the side mission team

742
00:36:16,197 --> 00:36:20,259
to help them integrate their missions into layouts that

743
00:36:20,279 --> 00:36:21,539
would be made specifically for them.

744
00:36:21,599 --> 00:36:24,140
And it's very important to know because when

745
00:36:24,240 --> 00:36:25,841
they needed some location, they would come to me

746
00:36:25,861 --> 00:36:29,402
and they would tell me, can you create something so that we

747
00:36:29,442 --> 00:36:30,163
could put our things?

748
00:36:31,063 --> 00:36:32,524
And that's how the sewers came to life.

749
00:36:32,584 --> 00:36:35,867
The sewers are great if you don't know them.

750
00:36:36,407 --> 00:36:39,870
And they're meant to help the side missions thrive

751
00:36:40,210 --> 00:36:41,171
by having their own layouts.

752
00:36:42,332 --> 00:36:44,994
And that's how every location that I made

753
00:36:45,034 --> 00:36:47,236
for the side missions, they take expression into account

754
00:36:47,296 --> 00:36:50,318
and it helps making them really harmonized

755
00:36:51,439 --> 00:36:54,202
according to the, with regard to the rest of the game.

756
00:36:55,876 --> 00:37:01,250
And another thing with SideMission is that they have a very small team, a multidisciplinary

757
00:37:01,290 --> 00:37:02,232
team that works very well.

758
00:37:02,252 --> 00:37:03,736
They have a writer, designers, scripters.

759
00:37:04,518 --> 00:37:05,260
But sometimes...

760
00:37:06,660 --> 00:37:09,823
They're really wild, so they might not always respect

761
00:37:10,564 --> 00:37:11,605
their sexist peers.

762
00:37:12,586 --> 00:37:14,067
For example, when I came onto the team,

763
00:37:14,087 --> 00:37:15,728
you would get ambushed in this very location.

764
00:37:16,389 --> 00:37:18,391
Some guys would just jump you, some pike your smirks,

765
00:37:19,412 --> 00:37:21,093
and they would just start a fight with you

766
00:37:21,133 --> 00:37:21,954
in the middle of the street,

767
00:37:21,974 --> 00:37:23,956
and that's something that might sound cool,

768
00:37:24,196 --> 00:37:25,097
but in this kind of game,

769
00:37:25,897 --> 00:37:27,599
you always have to let the player have a choice

770
00:37:27,879 --> 00:37:30,842
to fight or not to fight, so I removed that.

771
00:37:32,463 --> 00:37:35,544
And the cool thing about it is that I moved this setup

772
00:37:36,344 --> 00:37:38,225
of people attacking you in your own house

773
00:37:39,165 --> 00:37:40,925
because it was already planned for exploration.

774
00:37:41,005 --> 00:37:43,246
There's a multi-pass, multi-options already.

775
00:37:43,286 --> 00:37:44,867
You can escape via the windows.

776
00:37:46,207 --> 00:37:49,008
And I think that's something that is important to do

777
00:37:49,048 --> 00:37:50,108
when you have a team that is working.

778
00:37:51,200 --> 00:37:53,360
on the side and you don't have a lot of contact with them.

779
00:37:54,621 --> 00:37:56,522
It was, in our case, it worked,

780
00:37:56,622 --> 00:37:57,922
it made the mission better,

781
00:37:57,982 --> 00:37:59,202
it made the conversation that you have

782
00:37:59,222 --> 00:38:00,243
with the key character better.

783
00:38:00,723 --> 00:38:01,843
It supported gameplay better,

784
00:38:01,863 --> 00:38:03,284
you can stealth your way out.

785
00:38:03,544 --> 00:38:05,525
Now you can fight these guys, you can just hide.

786
00:38:06,205 --> 00:38:07,085
And it wasn't the case before,

787
00:38:07,145 --> 00:38:08,466
and it's very, very important to know

788
00:38:08,506 --> 00:38:10,166
what these guys are doing.

789
00:38:10,926 --> 00:38:12,587
Because, as I'm saying here,

790
00:38:12,687 --> 00:38:15,168
when a place perfectly fits within the world's world,

791
00:38:15,228 --> 00:38:15,628
it shows.

792
00:38:16,628 --> 00:38:17,208
And for side mission,

793
00:38:17,228 --> 00:38:19,029
it was very important to keep an eye on it.

794
00:38:21,814 --> 00:38:24,355
And that's another thing that I tended to do a lot,

795
00:38:25,115 --> 00:38:27,195
in addition to over-complexify my stories,

796
00:38:28,316 --> 00:38:29,456
is I wanted to connect everything,

797
00:38:31,136 --> 00:38:32,457
because I wasn't always realizing

798
00:38:32,497 --> 00:38:33,977
that other people were doing cool stuff,

799
00:38:34,637 --> 00:38:36,978
because we were alone, I'm gonna repeat that a lot,

800
00:38:37,018 --> 00:38:39,639
we were not a big team, we were experimenting,

801
00:38:39,659 --> 00:38:40,419
we were doing a lot of things.

802
00:38:42,019 --> 00:38:44,680
But sometimes I just wanted to, yeah,

803
00:38:44,820 --> 00:38:46,980
I was over-designing, and it's not sexy,

804
00:38:47,321 --> 00:38:48,881
it's not sexy because the word design is in it.

805
00:38:50,461 --> 00:38:51,842
And yeah, too many connection.

806
00:38:52,062 --> 00:38:53,945
I want to connect side missions to expression setups.

807
00:38:53,965 --> 00:38:57,208
I wanted to connect main stories with whatever.

808
00:38:57,248 --> 00:38:58,710
I was trying to connect the world.

809
00:38:58,970 --> 00:39:00,632
And it was just, again, small world feeling.

810
00:39:01,213 --> 00:39:01,914
We want to avoid that.

811
00:39:02,054 --> 00:39:03,736
And many connection makes the world look fake

812
00:39:04,617 --> 00:39:05,338
and convenient.

813
00:39:06,919 --> 00:39:09,703
So it's resisting the urge to do that.

814
00:39:11,608 --> 00:39:13,430
And now, philosophy on not blocking stuff

815
00:39:13,490 --> 00:39:17,714
is actually another thing that I had to fight about.

816
00:39:18,955 --> 00:39:20,897
We both had to fight about it, me and Jeff,

817
00:39:22,138 --> 00:39:23,339
the level designer who worked with me.

818
00:39:23,639 --> 00:39:26,782
We wanted to keep exploration content there at all times.

819
00:39:26,902 --> 00:39:29,325
We didn't want to block anything from the player.

820
00:39:29,385 --> 00:39:31,347
And then some of the guys in our team,

821
00:39:31,367 --> 00:39:33,128
they wanted to make exploration.

822
00:39:34,845 --> 00:39:36,086
in steps in some way.

823
00:39:36,106 --> 00:39:38,967
They wanted some contents to be locked during a visit

824
00:39:39,027 --> 00:39:40,168
and then you would come back to Prague

825
00:39:40,188 --> 00:39:41,388
and this would be magically unlocked.

826
00:39:42,048 --> 00:39:44,569
And as I said, with magic locks, they suck.

827
00:39:45,530 --> 00:39:49,591
So we had to fight for it because simple reasons.

828
00:39:50,171 --> 00:39:52,292
In Deus Ex, you don't have skill objects like in Zelda.

829
00:39:52,892 --> 00:39:54,233
Our skill objects are augmentations.

830
00:39:55,674 --> 00:39:58,014
And you can get augmentations or not.

831
00:39:58,174 --> 00:39:59,515
You can get whatever augmentations you want

832
00:39:59,535 --> 00:40:00,675
and we have no way of tracking

833
00:40:00,735 --> 00:40:01,956
what you're gonna be equipped with.

834
00:40:03,560 --> 00:40:06,601
And yeah, none of our augmentation are given through the main story.

835
00:40:07,201 --> 00:40:09,762
So we offer, Prague offers, and the whole game offers,

836
00:40:09,782 --> 00:40:12,903
skill-based exploration and not progression-based one.

837
00:40:12,963 --> 00:40:16,624
And that's what we explain to our leads and directors

838
00:40:16,664 --> 00:40:20,745
to not let them block accesses.

839
00:40:21,125 --> 00:40:22,986
Because when you see something, when you see an apartment

840
00:40:23,406 --> 00:40:25,266
and a balcony, you have to be able to get there and...

841
00:40:26,687 --> 00:40:29,990
we took specific care into making all these little

842
00:40:30,130 --> 00:40:31,111
augmentation challenges.

843
00:40:31,731 --> 00:40:33,273
So someone who gets augmented,

844
00:40:34,134 --> 00:40:35,595
they can have a party in Prague

845
00:40:35,615 --> 00:40:37,016
and be very happy about exploration.

846
00:40:37,076 --> 00:40:38,117
And that's good for us.

847
00:40:38,157 --> 00:40:40,700
And if, the thing is, if people explore

848
00:40:40,720 --> 00:40:42,701
the hell out of Prague and have seen people do it,

849
00:40:43,682 --> 00:40:47,303
read about people who were spending 10 hours in Prague during their first visit there and

850
00:40:47,323 --> 00:40:48,304
they were exploring everything.

851
00:40:49,384 --> 00:40:54,386
And some people were not happy about it because what if we don't have content later to offer

852
00:40:54,406 --> 00:40:54,546
them?

853
00:40:55,086 --> 00:40:56,647
And me, I was very excited about it.

854
00:40:56,707 --> 00:41:01,008
I was very excited about people finding everything during the first visit.

855
00:41:01,068 --> 00:41:05,170
It was cool, but it's a matter of respecting the game speeler.

856
00:41:07,900 --> 00:41:09,901
But there are exceptions, of course.

857
00:41:10,461 --> 00:41:13,123
We cannot just open everything all the time.

858
00:41:14,443 --> 00:41:16,024
If a setup is tied to a mission's timeline,

859
00:41:16,044 --> 00:41:18,545
we need to lock the out-of-context content.

860
00:41:19,686 --> 00:41:21,007
But if you have to lock something,

861
00:41:21,547 --> 00:41:23,888
you must make sure that the explored area

862
00:41:23,968 --> 00:41:25,649
remains interesting and useful,

863
00:41:26,650 --> 00:41:28,130
and tease the player into coming back.

864
00:41:28,190 --> 00:41:30,752
And that's something that is very hard to do, I think,

865
00:41:30,892 --> 00:41:33,773
is how do you convey to the player

866
00:41:33,813 --> 00:41:35,934
that if he comes back to a location later,

867
00:41:35,974 --> 00:41:36,735
it's gonna be different.

868
00:41:38,945 --> 00:41:42,188
there's no really magic things to do there,

869
00:41:42,208 --> 00:41:44,390
but what we did with this exception, this example,

870
00:41:44,471 --> 00:41:46,332
is that at some point you're gonna reach this apartment

871
00:41:47,553 --> 00:41:49,575
and you're gonna see these pictures of you

872
00:41:50,496 --> 00:41:53,259
and Vega, which is another key character in our game.

873
00:41:53,859 --> 00:41:55,401
So you see these pictures and hopefully...

874
00:41:56,342 --> 00:42:00,445
It teases you into coming back later because it's personal.

875
00:42:00,905 --> 00:42:01,546
It's a picture of you.

876
00:42:02,166 --> 00:42:03,647
So it involves you directly, and I

877
00:42:03,687 --> 00:42:06,049
think it makes it easier to convey the message that,

878
00:42:06,369 --> 00:42:09,051
if you come back, something may be different.

879
00:42:10,553 --> 00:42:13,155
And when you come back, it's actually different.

880
00:42:13,695 --> 00:42:14,656
There's a pragma.

881
00:42:14,696 --> 00:42:16,457
There's some guy apparently is talking to you.

882
00:42:18,227 --> 00:42:20,509
and you don't know who the hell it is, he is.

883
00:42:21,389 --> 00:42:23,031
And he's waiting for you in an area.

884
00:42:23,351 --> 00:42:26,614
And another thing that is interesting with that setup

885
00:42:26,674 --> 00:42:28,195
is that I couldn't have this guy being here

886
00:42:28,235 --> 00:42:30,297
before a certain critical path mission

887
00:42:30,937 --> 00:42:32,538
because it wouldn't have made sense at all.

888
00:42:32,598 --> 00:42:34,980
It's something we discussed with Mary Dermal,

889
00:42:35,000 --> 00:42:36,722
which is our executive narrative director.

890
00:42:37,543 --> 00:42:39,704
She said that it didn't make sense to have this guy,

891
00:42:39,744 --> 00:42:42,567
this train station cop who suffers from PTSD

892
00:42:42,667 --> 00:42:44,208
after the explosion that you witnessed

893
00:42:44,468 --> 00:42:45,349
at the beginning of the game.

894
00:42:46,590 --> 00:42:50,151
So I do something that usually never do, I spawn him.

895
00:42:51,331 --> 00:42:53,212
After you read an email and for exploration,

896
00:42:53,252 --> 00:42:56,013
something that we never do, but in exceptional case,

897
00:42:56,393 --> 00:43:00,314
like this guy, it's essential because else,

898
00:43:01,094 --> 00:43:03,755
actually before, you would encounter this guy again

899
00:43:03,795 --> 00:43:05,536
in a bike alley and he would just jump you

900
00:43:05,636 --> 00:43:08,417
and force you to fight him and yeah,

901
00:43:08,457 --> 00:43:09,337
that couldn't stay in the game.

902
00:43:09,917 --> 00:43:11,278
He had to remain consistent.

903
00:43:13,138 --> 00:43:19,226
Another thing that I just said, visiting the same place twice, most people don't do it

904
00:43:20,607 --> 00:43:23,751
because it doesn't make sense. They have no way of knowing if it's going to be different.

905
00:43:25,399 --> 00:43:28,460
And in our case, in our game, if a location is going to change,

906
00:43:28,700 --> 00:43:30,881
it should be the result of the player's action.

907
00:43:31,702 --> 00:43:32,682
Most of the time, we have...

908
00:43:33,563 --> 00:43:35,323
This is the example, I don't know if you remember,

909
00:43:35,383 --> 00:43:37,625
but the very first example I gave of an exploration setup

910
00:43:37,705 --> 00:43:40,146
is this guy, this crazy augmented dude

911
00:43:40,186 --> 00:43:42,587
who's apparently stealing things from the street

912
00:43:42,627 --> 00:43:44,168
and putting them on his little archway.

913
00:43:45,028 --> 00:43:48,350
I made three different versions of the props for this area.

914
00:43:49,390 --> 00:43:52,152
visit one, visit two of Prague and visit three. It's all going to be different. It's going

915
00:43:52,172 --> 00:43:58,136
to offer you some rewards, some narrative, little pocket secretaries with codes in there

916
00:43:58,156 --> 00:44:01,618
and you're going to discover what this guy is about, what he's doing. And since it's

917
00:44:01,658 --> 00:44:06,602
very easy to do, this propping, it's a very accessible area. It's worth it to do it if

918
00:44:06,642 --> 00:44:12,966
it's really cheap. Changing the environment for no reason else that I found it cool. But

919
00:44:12,986 --> 00:44:15,828
it still is an exception and you should do it pretty often.

920
00:44:18,042 --> 00:44:18,863
And that's a video.

921
00:44:19,303 --> 00:44:20,985
Without the sound, it's gonna be pretty boring.

922
00:44:21,445 --> 00:44:23,787
But it's a cat lady, it's a side mission apartment.

923
00:44:24,468 --> 00:44:26,910
And it's, the thing I was saying about

924
00:44:27,130 --> 00:44:29,112
if you have to lock content,

925
00:44:30,393 --> 00:44:33,316
the area must remain interesting, sorry.

926
00:44:33,476 --> 00:44:35,778
So this apartment is a side mission character.

927
00:44:36,199 --> 00:44:37,860
It's not active yet, you don't have the mission yet,

928
00:44:37,920 --> 00:44:41,143
but you can find all of these cool cat pictures

929
00:44:41,203 --> 00:44:42,304
and there's a cat shrine.

930
00:44:42,604 --> 00:44:44,746
And we made sure that it was intriguing and interesting.

931
00:44:45,367 --> 00:44:48,249
And you didn't hear it, but when you enter this apartment,

932
00:44:48,749 --> 00:44:51,391
there's a cat sound, meow, every time you enter.

933
00:44:52,032 --> 00:44:53,473
And this is my greatest accomplishment.

934
00:44:53,713 --> 00:44:55,354
Thanks for the audio guys for doing this.

935
00:44:56,715 --> 00:44:58,737
And that makes this apartment tremendously

936
00:45:00,298 --> 00:45:01,499
important and interesting.

937
00:45:02,940 --> 00:45:06,743
So, a little conclusion with a twist about design,

938
00:45:06,763 --> 00:45:08,944
because I'm not really done yet.

939
00:45:10,389 --> 00:45:13,732
Everything I just said, so I can sum it up with these phrases.

940
00:45:13,992 --> 00:45:17,156
Know what your people on your team do and how your own work can help.

941
00:45:17,817 --> 00:45:19,899
And that's my work with the Sight Mission Team

942
00:45:19,919 --> 00:45:23,443
that allowed me to really, really take that into practice.

943
00:45:25,164 --> 00:45:27,026
And play one to explore your world.

944
00:45:27,086 --> 00:45:29,109
If you need to block an area, justify the hell out of it.

945
00:45:29,649 --> 00:45:31,751
No crates before doors, please.

946
00:45:33,868 --> 00:45:35,209
unless it's the topic of your game

947
00:45:35,249 --> 00:45:37,470
and you want to explore this concept.

948
00:45:38,670 --> 00:45:40,211
Every constraint can have benefits.

949
00:45:40,471 --> 00:45:42,572
Think about how a constraint can enrich the experience.

950
00:45:42,592 --> 00:45:44,373
The example of the curfew, how it helped us

951
00:45:45,373 --> 00:45:48,235
make navigation better is a good example of that.

952
00:45:49,195 --> 00:45:50,736
And don't change things for the sake of it.

953
00:45:51,556 --> 00:45:52,817
If you want player to notice,

954
00:45:54,118 --> 00:45:56,139
find strong way to convey the message in.

955
00:45:58,527 --> 00:46:01,368
Yeah, that's what I did by putting the pictures of you

956
00:46:01,428 --> 00:46:03,290
on the wall of this guy so you would remember that.

957
00:46:04,230 --> 00:46:06,992
And LDs, we are keepers of the experience,

958
00:46:07,893 --> 00:46:09,554
but it doesn't mean you have to be rigid about it.

959
00:46:10,134 --> 00:46:14,937
Find ways, smart ways to twist the experience

960
00:46:14,997 --> 00:46:17,599
and it's something that I learned also by my contact

961
00:46:17,639 --> 00:46:21,601
with the side mission team who are like wild cards

962
00:46:21,701 --> 00:46:23,162
and they do all kinds of exotic stuff

963
00:46:23,202 --> 00:46:24,023
and it's very interesting.

964
00:46:25,790 --> 00:46:27,231
But, as I said, I'm not done yet.

965
00:46:28,152 --> 00:46:30,534
With this part, I'm gonna talk about what I've learned

966
00:46:30,554 --> 00:46:32,556
in a more personal way.

967
00:46:33,617 --> 00:46:36,038
Because as I said, this was a four and a half years project

968
00:46:36,099 --> 00:46:38,400
and we were a very small team in Prague for a long time.

969
00:46:38,761 --> 00:46:41,503
And there were some personal struggles

970
00:46:41,543 --> 00:46:42,404
that we've had to face.

971
00:46:42,584 --> 00:46:47,147
And me, as a junior, I was not always, you know,

972
00:46:47,628 --> 00:46:49,329
very detached from what I was doing.

973
00:46:50,913 --> 00:46:53,134
And if I'm just stepping back a little bit,

974
00:46:53,194 --> 00:46:58,096
I'm gonna explain the growing up process, I guess.

975
00:46:59,777 --> 00:47:03,439
With examples, I had exploration setups in our game

976
00:47:03,499 --> 00:47:05,900
that became main missions.

977
00:47:06,661 --> 00:47:10,863
And I'm gonna explain to you why I had issues with that.

978
00:47:12,702 --> 00:47:14,864
I don't know if you played the game,

979
00:47:14,904 --> 00:47:16,925
there's two missions, one is called Alicent Complex

980
00:47:17,165 --> 00:47:19,066
and the other is called Otar Casino.

981
00:47:19,086 --> 00:47:22,068
They're two main missions that used to be only explorations.

982
00:47:22,648 --> 00:47:24,709
So I was making them in Marlene Corner

983
00:47:24,729 --> 00:47:26,110
and I was happy doing my things.

984
00:47:28,009 --> 00:47:33,537
And at some point, they became big missions and I had problems, personal problems with

985
00:47:33,577 --> 00:47:33,637
it.

986
00:47:33,657 --> 00:47:37,922
I was afraid that because it was going to be part of the main story, it was going to

987
00:47:38,343 --> 00:47:42,188
be streamlined and less interesting in terms of design, that all of the cool stuff, the

988
00:47:42,228 --> 00:47:45,111
hidden stuff that I would put in there would disappear.

989
00:47:46,562 --> 00:47:48,644
And that was just because I was actually giving

990
00:47:48,724 --> 00:47:51,625
too much attention to the 1% of hardcore explorers,

991
00:47:52,286 --> 00:47:53,707
and I wasn't seeing the big picture enough.

992
00:47:54,907 --> 00:47:57,289
And that's why I took things so personally as well.

993
00:47:57,589 --> 00:47:59,710
So if I have this example of the casino,

994
00:47:59,770 --> 00:48:01,091
it was a simple exploration setups.

995
00:48:01,872 --> 00:48:05,654
It looks ugly, but I had the help of an artist.

996
00:48:05,714 --> 00:48:07,295
We were doing it kind of under the radar,

997
00:48:07,635 --> 00:48:09,496
and it was a lot better looking than this.

998
00:48:10,597 --> 00:48:11,497
We did it in secrecy.

999
00:48:12,878 --> 00:48:13,959
I gave it to the side mission team

1000
00:48:13,999 --> 00:48:14,959
because they needed a location.

1001
00:48:16,125 --> 00:48:17,206
to put one of the setups in.

1002
00:48:17,647 --> 00:48:19,549
And someday our gameplay director, Patrick,

1003
00:48:20,330 --> 00:48:22,752
he just stumbled upon it somehow

1004
00:48:22,812 --> 00:48:25,775
while exploring the many ways of the sewers.

1005
00:48:26,896 --> 00:48:30,840
He decided to make it a main mission area.

1006
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:33,343
So now you have this debate with this mafia guy.

1007
00:48:34,504 --> 00:48:36,286
And it's a really cool location.

1008
00:48:36,306 --> 00:48:39,069
But to me, it was a lose or lose situation.

1009
00:48:40,948 --> 00:48:46,432
I would have trouble getting out of my comfort zone, actually.

1010
00:48:46,512 --> 00:48:49,554
I was afraid it was going to suck, that a lot of people were going to work on it and

1011
00:48:49,574 --> 00:48:53,716
were taking basically the map from me and I was angry about it.

1012
00:48:54,817 --> 00:48:59,139
And I wasn't talking to anybody, so I had to get out of my seat.

1013
00:49:00,280 --> 00:49:06,084
and had to actually grab the people who were working on this area after it became a main story mission.

1014
00:49:06,104 --> 00:49:12,849
There were like 10 people now working on it and before that it was just me as a single nerd working on it.

1015
00:49:13,930 --> 00:49:17,233
And yes, I had to fight to keep the interesting content in it.

1016
00:49:17,273 --> 00:49:21,536
It's not because it became part of the main mission that it's not interesting anymore.

1017
00:49:21,616 --> 00:49:26,420
And another example of it that was pretty close to me is this guy, Joseph.

