00:49:39,864 --> 00:49:45,586
A map named Allison Complex came to life and my setup and this map had the same topic.

1021
00:49:45,706 --> 00:49:52,088
It was about people trying to reach the machine god and trying to connect to some mechanical

1022
00:49:52,128 --> 00:49:52,468
deity.

1023
00:49:53,008 --> 00:49:56,610
So I was thinking what is going to happen to my guy?

1024
00:49:56,630 --> 00:50:03,952
And at this point I was actually afraid again because we were very isolated for a long time

1025
00:50:05,212 --> 00:50:05,672
in our team.

1026
00:50:07,073 --> 00:50:10,877
I was kind of afraid to again lose some cool exploration things.

1027
00:50:11,998 --> 00:50:16,663
But again I had to think how to make this setup part of the main story

1028
00:50:17,163 --> 00:50:19,205
without ruining all of its intentions.

1029
00:50:19,706 --> 00:50:21,428
And actually I was kind of forced,

1030
00:50:21,448 --> 00:50:23,229
because I was afraid to talk to...

1031
00:50:24,885 --> 00:50:28,968
I was free to talk to our executive narrative director, Mary, she's very nice, but I was

1032
00:50:29,009 --> 00:50:33,112
kind of impressed by her, so I wasn't, you know, I was shy.

1033
00:50:33,673 --> 00:50:38,117
And one of my colleagues forced me to go talk to her and explain to her what my intentions

1034
00:50:38,157 --> 00:50:39,438
were with this setup.

1035
00:50:39,478 --> 00:50:45,023
So I set up a meeting and I was surprised that she was so open.

1036
00:50:46,204 --> 00:50:48,165
to, you know, I wasn't expecting it.

1037
00:50:49,266 --> 00:50:50,866
And what I've learned is that people usually

1038
00:50:51,027 --> 00:50:52,567
strive for good compromise and new option,

1039
00:50:52,627 --> 00:50:54,849
but three years ago I did not necessarily know that.

1040
00:50:56,609 --> 00:50:59,211
And now Joseph is happy again, he's still dead.

1041
00:51:00,051 --> 00:51:02,252
But he has a nice little custom animation pose

1042
00:51:02,272 --> 00:51:05,194
that I could never have gotten if I was,

1043
00:51:05,914 --> 00:51:07,695
if I remained alone with my little setup.

1044
00:51:07,895 --> 00:51:08,836
Like, again, a nerd.

1045
00:51:09,256 --> 00:51:10,817
And this is what his setup looks like now,

1046
00:51:10,897 --> 00:51:14,278
and the cool thing about it is that by actually moving my,

1047
00:51:15,932 --> 00:51:20,154
But to talk to the people who are responsible

1048
00:51:20,194 --> 00:51:22,035
for the experience, to Marie, to Jeff,

1049
00:51:22,095 --> 00:51:25,276
to our creative director, it actually made

1050
00:51:25,296 --> 00:51:26,237
the whole experience better.

1051
00:51:26,337 --> 00:51:28,958
Now this location has a lot more content

1052
00:51:29,138 --> 00:51:32,780
now that it was in the radar of our direction.

1053
00:51:33,360 --> 00:51:35,741
It got lots of resources put into it.

1054
00:51:35,801 --> 00:51:38,383
We have custom drawings, we have even conversation,

1055
00:51:38,743 --> 00:51:42,845
the absolute most expensive ingredient

1056
00:51:42,865 --> 00:51:43,705
that we have in Deus Ex.

1057
00:51:44,970 --> 00:51:48,074
And it's still cool, it's still a subtle little environment

1058
00:51:48,094 --> 00:51:51,237
setup that you can stumble into, it's very interesting.

1059
00:51:51,257 --> 00:51:55,942
Yeah, this guy is, he looks weird, but he's, yeah.

1060
00:51:56,042 --> 00:51:57,864
That's an additional conversation that is linking

1061
00:51:57,904 --> 00:52:00,166
this setup to the Allison complex mission,

1062
00:52:00,186 --> 00:52:02,028
so the two of them, they work separately,

1063
00:52:02,189 --> 00:52:03,470
and they can work together as well.

1064
00:52:05,953 --> 00:52:06,433
And that's...

1065
00:52:08,172 --> 00:52:08,913
the lesson from it.

1066
00:52:09,053 --> 00:52:10,495
So from two optional setups,

1067
00:52:11,276 --> 00:52:12,877
done in secrecy with no money,

1068
00:52:13,318 --> 00:52:14,979
we got two polished critical missions

1069
00:52:15,020 --> 00:52:16,121
supporting all of our pillars,

1070
00:52:17,142 --> 00:52:18,783
and some cool exploration areas

1071
00:52:18,844 --> 00:52:20,926
with their own storytelling reward in secret.

1072
00:52:23,588 --> 00:52:24,590
And what I've learned from this is

1073
00:52:24,610 --> 00:52:25,851
that optional content is great,

1074
00:52:26,371 --> 00:52:27,272
but it doesn't have to die

1075
00:52:27,332 --> 00:52:28,714
if it becomes part of a greater plan.

1076
00:52:30,889 --> 00:52:33,270
And if more resources are invested in a setup,

1077
00:52:33,490 --> 00:52:35,871
then it gains more chances to reach the quality

1078
00:52:35,891 --> 00:52:37,672
and content you originally wanted for it.

1079
00:52:38,052 --> 00:52:40,853
And that's something I didn't know before.

1080
00:52:40,893 --> 00:52:42,954
I thought I'm gonna do things on my own

1081
00:52:43,014 --> 00:52:45,675
and everything's gonna be fine, but really not.

1082
00:52:46,575 --> 00:52:48,576
And the last thing I'm gonna say,

1083
00:52:48,616 --> 00:52:49,556
and then I'm gonna be done,

1084
00:52:50,777 --> 00:52:52,817
is why so many secrets and why the fear?

1085
00:52:53,518 --> 00:52:55,238
Why did people from our direction

1086
00:52:55,578 --> 00:52:57,099
stumble upon locations that I did?

1087
00:52:57,199 --> 00:52:58,720
Why didn't they know everything?

1088
00:53:00,544 --> 00:53:05,326
It's the tricky part because things don't always go perfectly.

1089
00:53:05,386 --> 00:53:06,927
We have trouble communicating sometimes.

1090
00:53:07,067 --> 00:53:12,890
And in our case, we were feeling frustrated, the two of us, Jeff and me, the two designers

1091
00:53:12,930 --> 00:53:18,833
on Prague, because everybody else was working on our vertical slice and we were, we spent

1092
00:53:18,873 --> 00:53:21,514
a long time alone with ourselves and it drove us a bit crazy.

1093
00:53:22,678 --> 00:53:27,259
And yes, we lost perspective on what we were doing.

1094
00:53:28,260 --> 00:53:30,500
And we thought we had to do everything on our own

1095
00:53:30,540 --> 00:53:31,280
and talk to no one.

1096
00:53:32,181 --> 00:53:35,881
And it's partly our fault, it's partly nobody's fault.

1097
00:53:36,261 --> 00:53:39,022
But there's also another lesson that I've learned,

1098
00:53:39,082 --> 00:53:42,063
it's about the process of communicating things to people.

1099
00:53:42,563 --> 00:53:44,263
I was using this document, don't try to read it.

1100
00:53:45,704 --> 00:53:46,104
It's awful.

1101
00:53:46,464 --> 00:53:51,248
It's actually a working document that I made to detail every setup that I had.

1102
00:53:52,069 --> 00:53:57,073
And I made the naive mistake of sending this to everybody, asking them to read everything

1103
00:53:57,293 --> 00:53:59,475
and come back to me with...

1104
00:54:01,276 --> 00:54:06,141
And I was doing this document because I was feeling the need to justify myself all the

1105
00:54:06,161 --> 00:54:10,424
time because a lot of designer creating stories, doing things and trying to make things validated

1106
00:54:10,464 --> 00:54:11,025
by people.

1107
00:54:11,505 --> 00:54:16,029
It was making me very awkward with myself.

1108
00:54:17,825 --> 00:54:20,648
And I was overdesigning these things.

1109
00:54:20,668 --> 00:54:23,351
Overdesigning again sucks.

1110
00:54:24,913 --> 00:54:27,576
And now I learn from this that sending documents to people

1111
00:54:27,816 --> 00:54:30,640
and expecting them to read them and understand exactly what's

1112
00:54:30,680 --> 00:54:31,681
in your head doesn't work.

1113
00:54:32,021 --> 00:54:34,104
And it took me a while to realize it.

1114
00:54:35,090 --> 00:54:37,633
So now this detailed document I keep for myself

1115
00:54:38,473 --> 00:54:41,736
and I use more of this summed up version

1116
00:54:42,657 --> 00:54:44,639
that I made up a long time later.

1117
00:54:44,679 --> 00:54:47,021
I used this document, I was summing up pretty

1118
00:54:47,161 --> 00:54:49,043
what my intentions were for exploration content

1119
00:54:49,743 --> 00:54:52,386
and I knew that it resonates with Mary and Jeff

1120
00:54:52,466 --> 00:54:54,007
or creative director because they would,

1121
00:54:54,528 --> 00:54:57,270
they're interested in keeping our universe interesting

1122
00:54:58,111 --> 00:54:59,352
and yeah, short sentences.

1123
00:55:00,933 --> 00:55:01,033
And.

1124
00:55:03,224 --> 00:55:05,286
That's actually what my point is.

1125
00:55:06,087 --> 00:55:08,929
Is that I was criticizing control freaks.

1126
00:55:09,469 --> 00:55:09,710
Whoops.

1127
00:55:11,751 --> 00:55:11,932
Yeah.

1128
00:55:12,732 --> 00:55:14,454
But I became a control freak.

1129
00:55:14,474 --> 00:55:15,334
Every time someone would,

1130
00:55:16,135 --> 00:55:18,797
because the cavalry came in Prague later in the project.

1131
00:55:18,837 --> 00:55:20,959
Three years later, lots and lots of people

1132
00:55:21,019 --> 00:55:23,281
came working on Prague and we were overwhelmed.

1133
00:55:23,501 --> 00:55:24,342
Me and Jeff, we were like,

1134
00:55:24,742 --> 00:55:26,244
what are these people doing to our stuff?

1135
00:55:26,264 --> 00:55:27,385
It was scary.

1136
00:55:28,566 --> 00:55:29,146
But in the end,

1137
00:55:31,888 --> 00:55:37,070
I was overprotective, but I learned more and more to detach myself from my work because

1138
00:55:37,110 --> 00:55:41,853
it was just making me very sad, and it was not serving the project properly.

1139
00:55:42,773 --> 00:55:45,035
And yeah, who created what, it doesn't matter in the end.

1140
00:55:45,995 --> 00:55:48,056
And I had to care about the work and not how I felt.

1141
00:55:49,077 --> 00:55:53,920
That's the important lesson and if I have to give some human experience takeaways about my

1142
00:55:54,400 --> 00:56:00,685
four and a half years doing Prague, is that yeah, there's nothing magic. And the lessons are

1143
00:56:00,805 --> 00:56:06,209
designing for the 1% as I did a lot. It's okay as long as it doesn't take 100% of your time.

1144
00:56:07,149 --> 00:56:11,232
And it happened to me. I was thinking about it too much. Get back perspective and that

1145
00:56:11,272 --> 00:56:16,516
means letting go. Again, if you, it's a lot of ego. I wasn't realizing.

1146
00:56:17,817 --> 00:56:19,939
that it was an ego thing, but it actually was,

1147
00:56:19,979 --> 00:56:22,581
and I had to take a step back and think about

1148
00:56:23,222 --> 00:56:24,763
what my ideas could bring to the project

1149
00:56:24,823 --> 00:56:27,406
and that my ideas were not my own.

1150
00:56:27,986 --> 00:56:29,628
The beautiful thing that happens in video games

1151
00:56:29,848 --> 00:56:32,871
and any creative media is that ideas are cool on their own,

1152
00:56:32,911 --> 00:56:34,032
but they only get interesting

1153
00:56:35,113 --> 00:56:38,216
when they travel into other people's brain.

1154
00:56:38,836 --> 00:56:40,338
And that's actually the last point.

1155
00:56:41,339 --> 00:56:46,144
your ideas need to get dirty, driving into other people's mind and you stop being too

1156
00:56:46,184 --> 00:56:51,129
protective about them. And yeah, escape the intention to squeal all is an interesting

1157
00:56:51,189 --> 00:56:53,251
one because I was tempted a lot of times to just say it.

1158
00:56:54,869 --> 00:56:56,251
Okay, screw you all.

1159
00:56:56,711 --> 00:56:58,974
I'm just gonna not, I'm just gonna give my minimum.

1160
00:56:59,754 --> 00:57:03,238
But, because I saw some of my colleagues,

1161
00:57:03,479 --> 00:57:05,060
I shouldn't say that, but some people I knew,

